  "title": "Agamben's discussion of paradigms even includes examples of prototypes, such as the art of weaving in Plato's ‘Statesmen’ or Michel Foucault's panopticon (Ibid.).",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "content": "Prototypes as experiences of Kairos or paradigms are neither mere material objects nor intangible insights, ideas, or norms. They are precedents and examples of how things might be, including what communities we may create around them. Their purpose is to encourage individuals and communities to experiment and define their values and visions for the common future while remaining open to further exploration. As a means of Kairos, prototypes use knowledge and practice, science and technology, in an ‘exemplary’ way transforming present and future expectations. In the next sections, we will describe this as ‘future anterior’ and optatives that define how prototypes preserve the future(s) as open and public.",
      "summary": "Prototypes and paradigms are not just physical objects or intangible norms, but examples of possible futures. They encourage individuals and communities to experiment, define their values, and vision for the future. They use knowledge, science, and technology to transform present and future expectations.",
